post_text:
Here are a few important pieces of information as we prepare to start school next week:

Arrival is 7:55am.

The school will NOT be open before that. Students should not arrive early

Meals
We will be serving breakfast the first week.
We will not be serving lunch the first week.
Remember, ALL students are now eligible to receive free breakfast and lunch.

MSHS students:
High School students will enter and exit through the gym lobby doors
Middle School students will enter and exit through the ramp doors

Elementary students:
Everyone will enter through the main door. Students will stand outside with their class and will enter grouped with their class. There are designated areas for each class. Staff will be available to assist.

Masks are mandatory.

Students may wear a mask from home. It must be a mask. Face shields, neck buffs, kerchiefs, are not masks.
School will supply masks for anyone who needs one.

WE ARE GETTING SO EXCITED!!

post_text:
Community Picnic
We are excited to invite you to the 6th Annual Central Lake Community Picnic! Given all that is going on, this picnic will be a curbside pick up of a box dinner (catered by the Blue Pelican) and a family activity bag. Here are the details-
You must register! Registration has been extended to August 7th, please register here soon! https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/WD8YVLK
Drive to the Central Lake Middle/High School between 5 and 6 pm on Wednesday, Aug 12.
Enter the parking lot off Howard Street (where the buses line up for pick up and drop off).
Stay in your car and wear a face covering while items are being delivered to you.
A CLEO representative will deliver your meals, family activity bag and any prizes you have won to your car.
If possible, open your trunk and your things will be placed inside.
Head out to your chosen picnic spot and enjoy!
If you are comfortable, share pictures of your picnic on the CLEO Facebook/ Virtual Picnic Event Page.

post_text:
100% At-Home CLPS On-Line Learning for 2020-2021

Clarifications

‚Ä¢ Taking the Parent Survey - Transportation & At-Home Learning Option survey did NOT commit anyone to any option.
‚Ä¢ Families who want to enroll in the 100% At-Home CLPS On-Line Learning for 2020-2021 will be asked to submit a separate enrollment form. This enrollment form has not yet been made available.
‚Ä¢ Families who enroll in the 100% At-Home CLPS On-Line Learning for 2020-2021 will be committing to a full semester (Sept 2020 to January 2021).
‚Ä¢ Students who enroll in the 100% At-Home CLPS On-Line Learning for 2020-2021 are eligible to play on CLPS athletic teams and participate in CLPS extra-curriculars when available.

Stay tuned. As CLPS continues to develop our Return to School Preparedness Plan we will update our families with plans and procedures.

From our State School Board of Education and State Superintendent Rice:

The State Board of Education‚Äôs adopted resolution reads: ‚ÄúNo child asked to grow up in a pandemic and, to the absolute extent possible, no child should be harmed in his or her education by the fact that he or she did grow up in part during a pandemic.‚Äù

Good afternoon everyone! When you pull up, you will notice we are trying to reserve the parking spot right in front for curbside pickups. Please help us out with that. You are more than welcome to enter the store, but you will see another new sign asking that you do not enter without a face covering. We are just trying to comply with the directives from our Governor. If you do not have a face mask, we do have disposable ones we are selling either for $1.00 each, or you can get a 10 pack for $9.95. If you need to purchase one in order to enter, either call us for curbside delivery, or enter, purchase one at the front counter and put it on. We really do appreciate everyone's cooperation! We also have a pretty good supply of disposable gloves if you need any. Have a beautiful day!

post_text:
State Emergency Relief Energy CAP Increases

Effective April 1, 2020, State Emergency Relief (SER) caps for energy services are increasing to address household energy needs due to COVID-19 pandemic-related economic conditions. The cap increases will be functional in Bridges on Monday, April 27, 2020 and will remain in effect through the remainder of the fiscal year ending September 30, 2020.

These cap increases demonstrate active efforts by the department to take steps necessary to provide additional energy benefits to Michigan residents.

Important Facts
‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ Deliverable fuels (propane, fuel oil and coal) ‚Äì cap is increasing from $1200 to $1500
‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ Natural gas, wood, electricity and all other heat types ‚Äì cap is increasing from $850
to $1150
‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ The new cap will be applied to any SER energy request with a service request date of 4/1/20 or later once the new caps are increased in Bridges on 04/27/2020.
‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ Any SER applications previously processed and denied due to exceeding previous cap limits will not be reprocessed.
text:
State Emergency Relief Energy CAP Increases

Effective April 1, 2020, State Emergency Relief (SER) caps for energy services are increasing to address household energy needs due to COVID-19 pandemic-related economic conditions. The cap increases will be functional in Bridges on Monday, April 27, 2020 and will remain in effect through the remainder of the fiscal year ending September 30, 2020.

These cap increases demonstrate active efforts by the department to take steps necessary to provide additional energy benefits to Michigan residents.

Important Facts
‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ Deliverable fuels (propane, fuel oil and coal) ‚Äì cap is increasing from $1200 to $1500
‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ Natural gas, wood, electricity and all other heat types ‚Äì cap is increasing from $850
to $1150
‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ The new cap will be applied to any SER energy request with a service request date of 4/1/20 or later once the new caps are increased in Bridges on 04/27/2020.
‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ Any SER applications previously processed and denied due to exceeding previous cap limits will not be reprocessed.

post_text:
An update of the CLPS Meals for Kids:

With the closure of school until the end of the 2019-2020 school year, CLPS is happy to announce that our Meals for Kids program will remain open.

Week of April 6-10
CLOSED Mon April 6
Tues April 7 - Fri April 20
Meals will be dropped off via our bus routes as we have been doing,
MSHS Lobby will be open from 9:30 - 10:30 for pick up.

Week of April 13 - ?
Mondays -
PICK UP @ MSHS Lobby only
Tues through Fri -
Meals will be dropped off via our bus routes as we have been doing,
MSHS Lobby will be open from 9:30 - 10:30 for pick up.

If you have already been in touch with us and you are on our list there is no need to contact us again. You will remain on our list.

If you have NOT contacted us and want to be included please call.
231.544.3141 ext. 319
Leave a message
Your name
Bus Drop off or Pick Up
How many children in your home

REMEMBER - this meal program is for ALL children. Not just CLPS students. If you have a neighbor or someone you know please share this information.

Thank you!

Lenore Weaver

post_text: Good morning, Trojans. There is a lot of information out there - and sometimes it‚Äôs hard to filter through it all. We thought we‚Äôd try to simplify things a bit. So let‚Äôs start with a schedule. A routine. Here is an EXAMPLE. During this extended at-home-stay a daily routine can go a long way to alleviate stress and ward off unwanted behaviors. You can post this on a piece of paper on the frig or the bathroom mirror or on the front of the TV screen. You work out a schedule that works best for your family. Hang in there!! We are thinking of you and we miss you!

post_text:
The Michigan Department of Health and Human Services (MDHHS) has created a statewide hotline for COVID-19.Public health and other experts will answer health-related questions about COVID-19. The team can also direct residents, providers and more to the right resources in their local communities and in other state government departments. The hotline will be open seven days a week from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. at 1-888-535-6136.

They are also asking residents to create a Smart911 profile at www.smart911.com. The information you provide is kept private and is only accessible to the 9-1-1 Center when you call 9-1-1. If you do have to call us the phone number you are using will trigger a special screen allowing 9-1-1 operators to read whatever information you have added to your profile. This is especially important during these trying times.

Hey there Trojan Nation. Hope everyone is hanging in there. This beautiful sunny day feels a little contrary to our actual situation - but the situation is real, so continue to use good practices and stay home, stay healthy, and wash your hands.

We would like to stay in touch - so watch for daily posts from us - a few helpful hints, maybe some games or activities for you to engage with your children at home.

This is a strange and unusual time - but we can take advantage of the time as well. Enjoy your children. Enjoy your family. Experience the gratitude for being healthy, having healthy children and living in a community that truly does love its children.

Here are some great activities from Scholastic - and get outside today - in your yard - and breathe the fresh air. Maybe even open up your windows and air out the house.

https://classroommagazines.scholastic.com/support/learnathome.html

Antrim County's Winter Carnival- Saturday February 22nd

Free Event on Saturday February 22nd from 10:30am -12:30pm at Camp Hayo-Went-Ha in Central Lake. Bring the entire family out for indoor and outdoor fun geared for children ages 0-8, and FREE Lunch!

Indoor Activities Include:
Free lunch buffet
Crafts
Stories by the Fireplace
Face Painting
Ways to get your child moving

Outdoor Activities Include:
Zip Line
Snow Shoeing
Snow Fun
Snowy Day Guided Walk
